            "content": [
              {
                "type": "output_text",
                "text": "Do you mean “secondary agent” in a multi‑agent system, a backup/fallback agent, a support/assistant role, or something else? I’ll outline common meanings and what a secondary agent typically can do — tell me which fits and I’ll give concrete design or prompts.\n\nCommon roles and capabilities of a secondary agent\n\n1. Backup / failover\n- Take over tasks if the primary agent fails or is overloaded.\n- Provide degraded but reliable functionality (e.g., read‑only access, limited responses).\n- Perform health checks and trigger failover, and notify operators.\n\n2. Assistant / helper to a primary agent (delegation)\n- Handle small, well‑defined subtasks (information lookup, formatting, summarization).\n- Enrich responses with external data (DB/API lookups), then return to the primary.\n- Validate or sanitize primary agent outputs (QA/consistency checks).\n\n3. Triage / routing / orchestration\n- Classify requests and route to the proper specialist agent or human.\n- Collect context and prerequisites before handing off.\n- Sequence multi‑step workflows and manage state transitions.\n\n4. Monitoring / observability\n- Watch system metrics, logs, and user sessions.\n- Surface anomalies, perform automated remediation (retries, restarts), and alert humans.\n- Aggregate telemetry for audit and debugging.\n\n5. Security / governance layer\n- Enforce policies (data redaction, access control, compliance checks).\n- Filter or block sensitive actions and escalate exceptions.\n\n6. Human-in-the-loop facilitator\n- Prepare suggestions or summaries for human review.\n- Collect human feedback and apply it (retraining signals or immediate corrections).\n\n7. Domain specialist / microservice agent\n- Execute specialized tasks (NLP entity extraction, image recognition, billing calculations).\n- Provide high‑accuracy results for narrow domains that feed the primary agent’s response.\n\n8. Parallel worker / performance booster\n- Run parallel queries or computations to reduce latency.\n- Cache results, prefetch likely needed data.\n\nDesign considerations and best practices\n- Define clear scope and responsibilities to avoid conflicts between primary and secondary agents.\n- Minimize privileges for the secondary agent (principle of least privilege).\n- Make interactions idempotent and design safe retry/backoff behavior.\n- Add observability: logs, traces, and metrics for every handoff.\n- Use explicit protocols (APIs/messages) for handoff, including context snapshot and expected result format.\n- Plan escalation and human oversight for ambiguous or high‑risk decisions.\n\nExamples\n- Customer support: secondary agent triages tickets, drafts answers, and pulls order/customer data for the primary agent to finalize.\n- CI/CD: secondary agent runs tests and lints, reports results, and can auto‑create a draft PR for the main agent to merge.\n- Multi‑agent writing: secondary agent produces bullet outlines and references while the primary composes the final narrative.\n\nIf you tell me the specific system or scenario you mean (e.g., chatbot architecture, robotic system, business workflow), I’ll give a tailored list of concrete tasks, interfaces, and example message formats for the secondary agent.",
